SIEM Lab: SSH Brute Force Detection with Splunk
📌 Overview

This project demonstrates the deployment and use of Splunk Enterprise on Kali Linux to simulate and detect SSH brute-force attacks.

The lab replicates real-world SOC analyst workflows, including log ingestion, detection engineering, alert creation, and dashboard visualization.

🎯 Objectives
Deploy Splunk Enterprise on Kali Linux
Ingest and monitor Linux authentication logs (/var/log/auth.log)
Simulate SSH brute-force attacks
Develop detection queries using SPL
Build a real-time monitoring dashboard
Map detections to MITRE ATT&CK framework
🧰 Technologies Used
Kali Linux (VirtualBox)
Splunk Enterprise (SIEM)
Linux CLI (bash)
systemd / rsyslog (log management)
SSH (OpenSSH server)
⚙️ Lab Setup
1. Install Splunk
wget -O splunk.deb "https://download.splunk.com/products/splunk/releases/10.2.1/linux/splunk-10.2.1-c892b66d163d-linux-amd64.deb"
sudo dpkg -i splunk.deb
sudo apt --fix-broken install -y
2. Start Splunk
/opt/splunk/bin/splunk start --accept-license
3. Enable Boot Persistence
sudo /opt/splunk/bin/splunk enable boot-start -user ray
4. Configure Logging (Kali Fix)
sudo apt install rsyslog -y
sudo systemctl enable rsyslog
sudo systemctl start rsyslog
5. Enable SSH
sudo apt install openssh-server -y
sudo systemctl start ssh
sudo systemctl enable ssh
